[2;36m│[0m ### **thoughts**                                                             [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m The IDOR vulnerabilities are straightforward and critical. The `userId`      [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m parameter in both API endpoints is completely client-controlled without any  [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m server-side authorization verification.                                      [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m                                                                              [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m The profile page JavaScript reveals the current user's ID (13) and shows how [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m the APIs are called. The get_favorite_restaurants endpoint returns full user [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m data including username and all restaurant preferences for any user ID       [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m provided.                                                                    [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m                                                                              [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m Interestingly, user IDs 7, 8, 9, 11, and 12 return "User not authenticated"  [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m while others return data. This suggests either these users don't exist or    [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m have some different authentication state.                                    [2;36m│[0m
[2;36m│[0m                                                                              [2;36m│[0m
